<p><b>Number theory</b> is a branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Pure_mathematics" title=3D"Pure mathematics">pure mathematics</a> devo=
ted primarily to the study of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Integer" title=3D"Integer">integers</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Arithmetic_function" title=3D"Arithmetic function">arithmetic fun=
ctions</a>. Number theorists study <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime numbers</a> as well as the prop=
erties of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_object" tit=
le=3D"Mathematical object">mathematical objects</a> constructed from intege=
rs (for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" =
title=3D"Rational number">rational numbers</a>), or defined as generalizati=
ons of the integers (for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Algebraic_integer" title=3D"Algebraic integer">algebraic integers</a>).=20
</p><p>Integers can be considered either in themselves or as solutions to e=
quations (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_geometry" ti=
tle=3D"Diophantine geometry">Diophantine geometry</a>). Questions in number=
 theory can often be understood through the study of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_analysis" title=3D"Complex analysis">analytical<=
/a> objects, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_z=
eta_function" title=3D"Riemann zeta function">Riemann zeta function</a>, th=
at encode properties of the integers, primes or other number-theoretic obje=
cts in some fashion (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_numb=
er_theory" title=3D"Analytic number theory">analytic number theory</a>). On=
e may also study <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" titl=
e=3D"Real number">real numbers</a> in relation to rational numbers, as for =
instance how irrational numbers can be approximated by fractions (<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_approximation" title=3D"Dioph=
antine approximation">Diophantine approximation</a>).
</p><p>Number theory is one of the oldest branches of mathematics alongside=
 geometry. One quirk of number theory is that it deals with statements that=
 are simple to understand but are very difficult to solve. Examples of this=
 are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem" titl=
e=3D"Fermat's Last Theorem">Fermat's Last Theorem</a>, which was proved 358=
 years after the original formulation, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture" title=3D"Goldbach's conjecture">Goldbach'=
s conjecture</a>, which remains unsolved since the 18th century. German mat=
hematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" t=
itle=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a> (1777=E2=80=931855) =
once remarked, "Mathematics is the queen of the sciences=E2=80=94and number=
 theory is the queen of mathematics."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELong19721_=
1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_th=
eory#cite_note-FOOTNOTELong19721-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It was regarded as the epito=
me of pure mathematics, with no applications outside mathematics, until the=
 1970s, when prime numbers became the basis for the creation of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-key_cryptography" title=3D"Public-key =
cryptography">public-key cryptography</a> algorithms, such as the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem" title=3D"RSA cryptosyst=
em">RSA cryptosystem</a>.
</p>
