g/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-:1-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Number theory is closely related to arithmetic and some authors use =
the terms as synonyms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Howeve=
r, the word "arithmetic" is used today to mean the study of numerical opera=
tions and extends to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_numb=
er" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note=
-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> In a more specific sense, number theory is restricted to the=
 study of integers and focuses on their properties and relationships.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Number_theory#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Traditionally, it is known as high=
er arithmetic.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By the early t=
wentieth century, the term <i>number theory</i> had been widely adopted.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note =
1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The term number means whol=
e numbers, which refers to either the natural numbers or the integers.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-:4_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-:4-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:6_1=
1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_th=
eory#cite_note-:6-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-12"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_number_theory" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Elementary number theory">Elementary number t=
heory</a> studies aspects of integers that can be investigated using elemen=
tary methods such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_pr=
oof" title=3D"Elementary proof">elementary proofs</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:=
3_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number=
_theory#cite_note-:3-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Analytic_number_theory" title=3D"Analytic number theory">Analytic number=
 theory</a>, by contrast, relies on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Complex_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Complex numbers">complex =
numbers</a> and techniques from analysis and calculus.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theo=
ry#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algeb=
raic_number_theory" title=3D"Algebraic number theory">Algebraic number theo=
ry</a> employs <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_structure=
s" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Algebraic structures">algebraic structure=
s</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematics)"=
 title=3D"Field (mathematics)">fields</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ring (mathematics)">rings</a> to a=
nalyze the properties of and relations between numbers. <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_number_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Geometric number theory">Geometric number theory</a> uses concepts from=
 geometry to study numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-15"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Further branches of number theory are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Probabilistic_number_theory" title=3D"Probabilistic number theory">pr=
