<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jayadeva_(mathematician)" title=3D=
"Jayadeva (mathematician)">Jayadeva</a>; the earliest surviving exposition =
appears in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bh%C4%81skara_II" title=
=3D"Bh=C4=81skara II">Bh=C4=81skara II</a>'s B=C4=ABja-ga=E1=B9=87ita (twel=
fth century).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPlofker2008194_43-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-FOO=
TNOTEPlofker2008194-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the early ninth century, the caliph <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Al-Ma%27mun" title=3D"Al-Ma'mun">al-Ma'mun</a> ordered translat=
ions of many Greek mathematical works and at least one Sanskrit work.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Number_theory#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Plofnot_45-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theor=
y#cite_note-Plofnot-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Diophantus's main work, the <i>Arithmetica</i>, was translated into Arabic =
by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qusta_ibn_Luqa" title=3D"Qusta =
ibn Luqa">Qusta ibn Luqa</a> (820=E2=80=93912).
Part of the treatise <i>al-Fakhri</i> (by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Al-Karaj%C4%AB" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Al-Karaj=C4=AB">al-K=
araj=C4=AB</a>, 953&nbsp;=E2=80=93 c.&nbsp;1029) builds on it to some exten=
t. According to Rashed Roshdi, Al-Karaj=C4=AB's contemporary <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibn_al-Haytham" title=3D"Ibn al-Haytham">Ibn al-=
Haytham</a> knew<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERashed1980305=E2=80=93321_46-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory=
#cite_note-FOOTNOTERashed1980305%E2%80%93321-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> what would lat=
er be called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilson%27s_theorem" t=
itle=3D"Wilson's theorem">Wilson's theorem</a>. Other than a treatise on sq=
uares in arithmetic progression by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Fibonacci" title=3D"Fibonacci">Fibonacci</a> no number theory to speak of =
was done in western Europe during the Middle Ages. Matters started to chang=
e in Europe in the late <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renaissanc=
e" title=3D"Renaissance">Renaissance</a>, thanks to a renewed study of the =
works of Greek antiquity. A catalyst was the textual emendation and transla=
tion into Latin of Diophantus' <i>Arithmetica</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#c=
ite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pierre_de_Fermat.png" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4=
b/Pierre_de_Fermat.png/250px-Pierre_de_Fermat.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"200" height=3D"354" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"566" d=
ata-file-height=3D"1003"></a><figcaption>Fermat is sometimes considered the=
 founder of modern number theory.</figcaption></figure>
<p>French mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_de_=
Fermat" title=3D"Pierre de Fermat">Pierre de Fermat</a> (1607=E2=80=931665)=
 never published his writings but communicated through correspondence and w=
rote in marginal notes instead.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWeil198445=E2=80=
=9346_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nu=
mber_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWeil198445%E2%80%9346-48"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> His con=
tributions to number theory brought renewed interest in the field in Europe=
. He conjectured <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_little=
_theorem" title=3D"Fermat's little theorem">Fermat's little theorem</a>, a =
basic result in modular arithmetic, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem" title=3D"Fermat's Last Theorem">Fermat's Las=
t Theorem</a>, as well as proved <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ermat%27s_right_triangle_theorem" title=3D"Fermat's right triangle theorem"=
>Fermat's right triangle theorem</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:7_2-1" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-=
:7-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He also s=
tudied prime numbers, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-squ=
are_theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Four-square theorem">four-squar=
e theorem</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pell%27s_equati=
ons" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pell's equations">Pell's equations</a>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNO=
TEWeil198492_51-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWeil198492-51"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The interest of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Eu=
ler" title=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a> (1707=E2=80=931783) in num=
ber theory was first spurred in 1729, when a friend of his, the amateur<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note=
 4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Goldbach" title=3D"Christian Goldbach">Christian =
Goldbach</a>, pointed him towards some of Fermat's work on the subject.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWeil19842,_172_53-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWeil19842,_1=
72-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVaradarajan20069_54-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_=
note-FOOTNOTEVaradarajan20069-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This has been called the "reb=
irth" of modern number theory,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWeil19841=E2=80=
=932_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Num=
ber_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWeil19841%E2%80%932-55"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> after Ferm=
at's relative lack of success in getting his contemporaries' attention for =
the subject.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-56"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He proved Fer=
mat's assertions, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat=
%27s_little_theorem" title=3D"Fermat's little theorem">Fermat's little theo=
rem</a>; made initial work towards a proof that every integer is the sum of=
 four squares;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWeil1984178=E2=80=93179_57-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cit=
e_note-FOOTNOTEWeil1984178%E2%80%93179-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and specific cases o=
f Fermat's Last Theorem.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-58"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 He wrote on the link between <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simp=
le_continued_fraction" title=3D"Simple continued fraction">continued fracti=
ons</a> and Pell's equation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Eulpell_59-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-Eul=
pell-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWeil1984183_60-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note=
-FOOTNOTEWeil1984183-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He made the first steps towards analyt=
ic number theory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Three European contemporaries continued the work in elementary numbe=
r theory. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph-Louis_Lagrange" t=
itle=3D"Joseph-Louis Lagrange">Joseph-Louis Lagrange</a> (1736=E2=80=931813=
) gave full proofs of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-squ=
are_theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Four-square theorem">four-squar=
e theorem</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilson%27s_theorem"=
 title=3D"Wilson's theorem">Wilson's theorem</a>, and developed the basic t=
heory of Pell's equations. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrien-=
Marie_Legendre" title=3D"Adrien-Marie Legendre">Adrien-Marie Legendre</a> (=
1752=E2=80=931833) stated the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quad=
ratic_reciprocity" title=3D"Quadratic reciprocity">law of quadratic recipro=
city.</a> He also conjectured what amounts to the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number_theorem" title=3D"Prime number theorem">prime =
number theorem</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirichlet%2=
7s_theorem_on_arithmetic_progressions" title=3D"Dirichlet's theorem on arit=
hmetic progressions">Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions</a>. He=
 gave a full treatment of the equation <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-=
math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-=
a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/M=
athML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle ax^{2}+by^{2}+cz^{2}=3D0}">
