ed the theory of quadratic forms. He also introduced some basic notation to=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruences" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Congruences">congruences</a> and devoted a section to computatio=
nal matters, including primality tests.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGoldstei=
nSchappacher200714_65-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGoldsteinSchappacher200714-65"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> He established a link between <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Roots_of_unity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Roots of unity">roots=
 of unity</a> and number theory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-66"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> In this way, Gauss arguably made forays towards <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89variste_Galois" title=3D"=C3=89variste Galois">=
=C3=89variste Galois</a>'s work and the area <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Algebraic_number_theory" title=3D"Algebraic number theory">algeb=
raic number theory</a>.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Georg_Friedrich_Bernhard_Riemann.jpeg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/8/82/Georg_Friedrich_Bernhard_Riemann.jpeg/250px-Georg_Fried=
rich_Bernhard_Riemann.jpeg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"273"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"903" data-file-height=3D"986"=
></a><figcaption>The Riemann hypothesis is of interest in analytic number t=
heory.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Starting early in the nineteenth century, the following developments gra=
dually took place:
</p>
<ul><li>The rise to self-consciousness of number theory (or <i>higher arith=
metic</i>) as a field of study.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-67"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup></li>
<li>The development of much of modern mathematics necessary for basic moder=
n number theory: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_analysis"=
 title=3D"Complex analysis">complex analysis</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Group_theory" title=3D"Group theory">group theory</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galois_theory" title=3D"Galois theory"=
>Galois theory</a>=E2=80=94accompanied by greater rigor in analysis and abs=
traction in algebra.</li>
<li>The rough subdivision of number theory into its modern subfields=E2=80=
=94in particular, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_number_=
theory" title=3D"Analytic number theory">analytic</a> and algebraic number =
theory.</li></ul>
<p>Algebraic number theory may be said to start with the study of reciproci=
ty and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclotomy" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Cyclotomy">cyclotomy</a>, but truly came into its own with t=
he development of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algebra=
" title=3D"Abstract algebra">abstract algebra</a> and early ideal theory an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valuation_(algebra)" title=3D"Va=
luation (algebra)">valuation</a> theory; see below. A conventional starting=
 point for analytic number theory is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Dirichlet%27s_theorem_on_arithmetic_progressions" title=3D"Dirichlet's t=
heorem on arithmetic progressions">Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progre=
ssions</a> (1837),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEApostol19767_68-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-=
FOOTNOTEApostol19767-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDavenportMo=
ntgomery20001_69-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavenportMontgomery20001-69"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> whose proof introduced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L-funct=
ions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"L-functions">L-functions</a> and invol=
ved some asymptotic analysis and a limiting process on a real variable.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The first use of analytic ide=
as in number theory actually goes back to Euler (1730s),<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-FOOTNOTEIwaniecKowalski20041_71-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEIwaniecKowalski20041-=
71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVaradarajan2006sections_2.5,_3.1=
_and_6.1_72-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Number_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVaradarajan2006sections_2.5,_3.1_and_6.1-7=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> who used formal power series and non-rigorous (or implicit) =
limiting arguments. The use of <i>complex</i> analysis in number theory com=
es later: the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Rie=
mann" title=3D"Bernhard Riemann">Bernhard Riemann</a> (1859) on the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_zeta_function" title=3D"Riemann z=
eta function">zeta function</a> is the canonical starting point;<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGranville2008322=E2=80=93348_73-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGranv=
ille2008322%E2%80%93348-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Jacobi%27s_four-square_theorem" title=3D"Jacobi's four-square theorem=
">Jacobi's four-square theorem</a> (1839), which predates it, belongs to an=
 initially different strand that has by now taken a leading role in analyti=
c number theory (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_form" tit=
le=3D"Modular form">modular forms</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-74" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-74=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Mathematical_S=
ociety" title=3D"American Mathematical Society">American Mathematical Socie=
ty</a> awards the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cole_Prize" t=
itle=3D"Cole Prize">Cole Prize</a> in Number Theory</i>. Moreover, number t=
heory is one of the three mathematical subdisciplines rewarded by the <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat_Prize" title=3D"Fermat Prize"=
>Fermat Prize</a></i>.
</p>
