</p><p>Elementary number theory studies the divisibility properties of inte=
gers such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parity_(mathematics)"=
 title=3D"Parity (mathematics)">parity</a> (even and odd numbers), <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Prime numbers">prime numbers</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Perfect_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Perfect numbers">p=
erfect numbers</a>. Important number-theoric functions include the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisor_function" title=3D"Divisor functi=
on">divisor-counting function</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Divisor_summatory_function" title=3D"Divisor summatory function">divis=
or summatory function</a> and its modifications, and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_totient_function" title=3D"Euler's totient fun=
ction">Euler's totient function</a>. A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime number</a> is an integer gr=
eater than 1 whose only positive divisors are 1 and the prime itself. A pos=
itive integer greater than 1 that is not prime is called a composite number=
. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_theorem" title=3D"Euc=
lid's theorem">Euclid's theorem</a> demonstrates that there are infinitely =
many prime numbers that comprise the set {2, 3, 5, 7, 11, ...}. The <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sieve_of_Eratosthenes" title=3D"Sieve of =
Eratosthenes">sieve of Eratosthenes</a> was devised as an efficient algorit=
hm for identifying all primes up to a given natural number by eliminating a=
ll composite numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-81"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorization" title=3D"Fac=
torization">Factorization</a> is a method of expressing a number as a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_(mathematics)" title=3D"Product=
 (mathematics)">product</a>. Specifically in number theory, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_factorization" title=3D"Integer factoriza=
tion">integer factorization</a> is the decomposition of an integer into a p=
roduct of integers. The process of repeatedly applying this procedure until=
 all factors are prime is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Prime_factorization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prime factorization">p=
rime factorization</a>. A fundamental property of primes is shown in <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_lemma" title=3D"Euclid's lemm=
a">Euclid's lemma</a>. It is a consequence of the lemma that if a prime div=
ides a product of integers, then that prime divides at least one of the fac=
tors in the product. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundament=
al_theorem_of_arithmetic" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of arithmetic">uniqu=
e factorization theorem</a> is the fundamental theorem of arithmetic that r=
elates to prime factorization. The theorem states that every integer greate=
r than 1 can be factorised into a product of prime numbers and that this fa=
ctorisation is unique up to the order of the factors. For example, <span cl=
