=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>One may ask analytic questions about <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Algebraic_number" title=3D"Algebraic number">algebraic numbers</a=
>, and use analytic means to answer such questions; it is thus that algebra=
ic and analytic number theory intersect. For example, one may define <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_ideal" title=3D"Prime ideal">prime=
 ideals</a> (generalizations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pr=
ime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime numbers</a> in the field of algebr=
aic numbers) and ask how many prime ideals there are up to a certain size. =
This question <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landau_prime_ideal_t=
heorem" title=3D"Landau prime ideal theorem">can be answered</a> by means o=
f an examination of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dedekind_zeta_=
function" title=3D"Dedekind zeta function">Dedekind zeta functions</a>, whi=
ch are generalizations of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riem=
ann_zeta_function" title=3D"Riemann zeta function">Riemann zeta function</a=
>, a key analytic object at the roots of the subject.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-91=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theor=
y#cite_note-91"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> This is an example of a general procedure in an=
alytic number theory: deriving information about the distribution of a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequence" title=3D"Sequence">sequence<=
/a> (here, prime ideals or prime numbers) from the analytic behavior of an =
appropriately constructed complex-valued function.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_92=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_the=
ory#cite_note-:0-92"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Elementary number theory works with <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Elementary_proof" title=3D"Elementary proof">elementary proofs<=
/a></i>, a term that excludes the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Complex_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Complex numbers">com=
plex numbers</a> but may include basic analysis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_76-1=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theor=
y#cite_note-:2-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Prime_number_theorem" title=3D"Prime number theorem">prime nu=
mber theorem</a> was first proven using complex analysis in 1896, but an el=
ementary proof was found only in 1949 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Paul_Erd%C5%91s" title=3D"Paul Erd=C5=91s">Erd=C5=91s</a> and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atle_Selberg" title=3D"Atle Selberg">Sel=
berg</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGoldfeld2003_93-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTEG=
oldfeld2003-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> The term is somewhat ambiguous. For example, pr=
oofs based on complex <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tauberian_th=
eorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tauberian theorem">Tauberian theorems=
</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiener%E2%80%93Ikeha=
ra_theorem" title=3D"Wiener=E2=80=93Ikehara theorem">Wiener=E2=80=93Ikehara=
</a>, are often seen as quite enlightening but not elementary despite using=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_analysis" title=3D"Fourie=
r analysis">Fourier analysis</a>, not complex analysis. Here as elsewhere, =
an <i>elementary</i> proof may be longer and more difficult for most reader=
s than a more advanced proof.
</p><p>Some subjects generally considered to be part of analytic number the=
ory (e.g., <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sieve_theory" title=3D"=
Sieve theory">sieve theory</a>) are better covered by the second rather tha=
n the first definition.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-94" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-94"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Small sieves, for instance, use little analysis and yet still belong t=
o analytic number theory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-95" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-95"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
