ikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_reciprocity" title=3D"Quadratic reciprocity">qu=
adratic reciprocity</a>.
</p><p>Number fields are often studied as extensions of smaller number fiel=
ds: a field <i>L</i> is said to be an <i>extension</i> of a field <i>K</i> =
if <i>L</i> contains <i>K</i>.
(For example, the complex numbers <i>C</i> are an extension of the reals <i=
>R</i>, and the reals <i>R</i> are an extension of the rationals <i>Q</i>.)
Classifying the possible extensions of a given number field is a difficult =
and partially open problem. Abelian extensions=E2=80=94that is, extensions =
<i>L</i> of <i>K</i> such that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Galois_group" title=3D"Galois group">Galois group</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-9=
8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theo=
ry#cite_note-98"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 7<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Gal(<i>L</i>/<i>K</i>) of <i>L</i> over <i=
>K</i> is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abelian_group" title=
=3D"Abelian group">abelian group</a>=E2=80=94are relatively well understood=
.
Their classification was the object of the programme of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Class_field_theory" title=3D"Class field theory">clas=
s field theory</a>, which was initiated in the late nineteenth century (par=
tly by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leopold_Kronecker" title=3D=
"Leopold Kronecker">Kronecker</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Gotthold_Eisenstein" title=3D"Gotthold Eisenstein">Eisenstein</a>) and =
carried out largely in 1900=E2=80=931950.
</p><p>An example of an active area of research in algebraic number theory =
is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iwasawa_theory" title=3D"Iwasaw=
a theory">Iwasawa theory</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Langlands_program" title=3D"Langlands program">Langlands program</a>, one o=
f the main current large-scale research plans in mathematics, is sometimes =
described as an attempt to generalise class field theory to non-abelian ext=
ensions of number fields.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Diophantine_geometry">Dioph=
antine geometry</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
