Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilistic_number=
_theory" title=3D"Probabilistic number theory">Probabilistic number theory<=
/a></div><p>
Probabilistic number theory starts with questions such as the following: Ta=
ke an integer <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</=
span> at random between one and a million. How likely is it to be prime? (t=
his is just another way of asking how many primes there are between one and=
 a million). How many prime divisors will <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> have on average? What is the probability =
that it will have many more or many fewer divisors or prime divisors than t=
he average?<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Templ=
ateStyles:r1320445320"></p><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-n=
ot-searchable">Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arit=
hmetic_combinatorics" title=3D"Arithmetic combinatorics">Arithmetic combina=
torics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Additive_number_the=
ory" title=3D"Additive number theory">Additive number theory</a></div>
<p>Combinatorics in number theory starts with questions like the following:=
 Does a fairly "thick" <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_se=
t" title=3D"Infinite set">infinite set</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element =
mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mat=
hml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Ma=
th/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle A}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
