></span>?<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Templat=
eStyles:r1320445320"></p><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not=
-searchable">Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computa=
tional_number_theory" title=3D"Computational number theory">Computational n=
umber theory</a></div><figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/T=
humb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Computer_History_Museum=
_(4145886786).jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload=
.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Computer_History_Museum_%284145=
886786%29.jpg/250px-Computer_History_Museum_%284145886786%29.jpg" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"375" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"3164" data-file-height=3D"4752"></a><figcaption>A <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lehmer_sieve" title=3D"Lehmer sieve">Lehmer sieve=
</a>, a primitive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_computer=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Digital computer">digital computer</a> use=
d to find <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primes" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Primes">primes</a> and solve simple <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_equations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Diop=
hantine equations">Diophantine equations</a></figcaption></figure><p>There =
are two main questions: "Can this be computed?" and "Can it be computed rap=
idly?" Anyone can test whether a number is prime or, if it is not, split it=
 into prime factors; doing so rapidly is another matter. Fast algorithms fo=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primality_test" title=3D"Primali=
ty test">testing primality</a> are now known, but, in spite of much work (b=
oth theoretical and practical), no truly fast algorithm for factoring.
</p><div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applicati=
ons</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DNumber_t=
heory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Application=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>For a long time, number theory in general, and the study of prime number=
s in particular, was seen as the canonical example of pure mathematics, wit=
h no applications outside of mathematics other than the use of prime number=
ed gear teeth to distribute wear evenly.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-100" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-=
100"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>92<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> In particular, number theorists such as <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" title=3D"United Kingdom">British</a>=
 mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G._H._Hardy" title=
=3D"G. H. Hardy">G. H. Hardy</a> prided themselves on doing work that had a=
bsolutely no military significance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-101" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-101">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> The number-theorist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le=
onard_Dickson" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Leonard Dickson">Leonard Dick=
son</a> (1874=E2=80=931954) said "Thank God that number theory is unsullied=
 by any application". Such a view is no longer applicable to number theory.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-102" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-102"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>This vision of the purity of number theory was shattered in the 1970=
s, when it was publicly announced that prime numbers could be used as the b=
asis for the creation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-ke=
y_cryptography" title=3D"Public-key cryptography">public-key cryptography</=
a> algorithms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-103" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-103"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>95<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Schemes s=
uch as RSA are based on the difficulty of factoring large composite numbers=
 into their prime factors.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-104" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-104"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> These applications have led to significant study of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithms</a> for comp=
uting with prime numbers, and in particular of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Primality_test" title=3D"Primality test">primality testing</a>=
, methods for determining whether a given number is prime. Prime numbers ar=
e also used in computing for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Check=
sum" title=3D"Checksum">checksums</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Hash_table" title=3D"Hash table">hash tables</a>, and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number_generator" title=3D"Pseudorand=
om number generator">pseudorandom number generators</a>.
</p><p>In 1974, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Knuth" titl=
e=3D"Donald Knuth">Donald Knuth</a> said "virtually every theorem in elemen=
tary number theory arises in a natural, motivated way in connection with th=
e problem of making computers do high-speed numerical calculations".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-105" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Number_theory#cite_note-105"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>97<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Elementary number theory is taught in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Discrete_mathematics" title=3D"Discrete mathematics">discrete mathemati=
cs</a> courses for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_scient=
ist" title=3D"Computer scientist">computer scientists</a>. It also has appl=
ications to the continuous in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nume=
rical_analysis" title=3D"Numerical analysis">numerical analysis</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-106" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Number_theory#cite_note-106"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>98<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Number theory has now several modern applications spanning diverse a=
reas such as:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D=
"Computer science">Computer science</a>: The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform" title=3D"Fast Fourier transform">fast Fo=
urier transform</a> (FFT) algorithm, which is used to efficiently compute t=
he discrete Fourier transform, has important applications in signal process=
ing and data analysis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-107" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-107"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>99<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">Phy=
sics</a>: The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_hypothesis" =
title=3D"Riemann hypothesis">Riemann hypothesis</a> has connections to the =
distribution of prime numbers and has been studied for its potential implic=
ations in physics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-108" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-108"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>100<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Error_correction_code" title=
=3D"Error correction code">Error correction codes</a>: The theory of finite=
 fields and algebraic geometry have been used to construct efficient error-=
correcting codes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-109" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-109"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>101<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Study of musical scales: the concept of "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Equal_temperament" title=3D"Equal temperament">equal temperament=
</a>", which is the basis for most modern Western music, involves dividing =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octave" title=3D"Octave">octav=
e</a> into 12 equal parts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-110" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory#cite_note-110"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>102<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> This has been studied using number theory and in particular the propert=
ies of the 12th root of 2.</li></ul>
